Hi we are **Coral**, a team of engineers from web2 companies like Meta/Uber/Amazon. We are building the first-ever observability and transparency OS for web3 treasuries and contributors, aka AppDynamics for the ecosystem. 

The current ecosystem faces the following challenges:
1. Not enough understanding of how the treasury (split into native/non-native etc.) has been performing in the past and how it is expected to perform in future
2. No single point of view for all of your wallets, thereby making consolidation of transactions and bookkeeping a nightmare!
3. Contributors have no way to see their payroll/rewards/expenses and how they changed over time in a single interface, making the experience harder for them.
4. Existing systems do not incorporate defi analytics and hence are not complete.
5. Transparency is not emphasized enough.

We are building a system for:

**Web3 projects / DAOs / communities**
We are building an analytics system that will provide the following functionalities:
1. Balances of various wallets, total treasury value, and incoming and outgoing transactions across multiple wallets combined in a single dashboard and a way to visit the historical data
2. Relative asset holdings and value and information on how the native token has changed in value over time
Rule engine and auto-categorization to apply rules and categorize txn automatically when a particular condition is met
3. Discord integration and public dashboard for increased transparency
4. Defi analytics support

**Contributors of the web3 ecosystem**
Now the contributors get to track their finances efficiently. We provide the following analytics for them:
1. Payroll/rewards they earned from a particular DAO or combined across all DAOs and a way to see how they changed over time
2. A way for the contributors to submit expenses and understand which stage their expenses are currently in.
3. Get notified when a payment is made, or a reward is received. Also, never miss important events like your coordinape payment requirements, etc. through our reminder support.

The agency problem is a conflict of interest that occurs when agents (e.g. managers) don't fully represent the best interests of principals (e.g. shareholders/owners). In DAOs, the members are both the principal and the agent.

Are some of you interested to help make research literature less outdated? Interviews will be around 30min only. Please let me know.

2. After one year alice withdraws, burning MCv2Pool tokens and receives MC tokens back (either deposit or deposit + reward)

Is this flow correct or is there an additional step, like rewards are send to the escrow and eMC is received?

The MC is still escrowed but it is within the smart contract and auto claimed.

The lock period is specific to the amount deposited. Rewards are available for claiming 1year after they were earned in V2.

For V2:

1) Alice deposits MC into MCv2 pool with a 1year lock and receives SMC.
2) Throughout the year Alice earns MC every day which is locked for 1year from the day it's earned. 
3) After 1year the locked amount is withdrawable.
4) 1year after each batch of rewards is earned (daily) they are available to be claimed

Had 2 things to ask. Been an investor in MC since the LBP. 1) Have you'll looked at treeverse and played the pre-alpha? Does merit circle only invest in seed or venture deals or does it even buy NFTs of games from the secondary market?   2) Wanted to ask about deployment of funds. There is yet quite a bit of cash yet left on the balance sheet. When do you expect that to get deployed? Is the deployment taking more time than expected? And is the cash in interest bearing protocols or vaults?

Hi Divyam!

Actually in touch with Treeverse, def. want to get early access to check it out heheheh.

As far as buying NFTs goes, so far this has only happened through venture deals. However, we're definitely intending on also purchasing a bunch from the secondary market in the (near) future. We've large scaled out scholarship games, however, do see a fit for having smaller numbers of NFTs for games that we notice the community is interested in, simply to get them in people's hands to enable them to try the game before having to purchase the NFTs yourself.

As far as 2 goes, this is actually on purpose. Investments have slowed down and due diligence is significantly more strict than it was during the bull run (1. because of short-term profit expectations but also 2. because we simply have hired more knowledgable and skilled analysts). So, it's not unexpected I would say. On top of that, it's also extremely healthy for the DAO to maintain a minimum cash position of say $50M to navigate the volatile waters. Allows for continuous developments of own products, DAO grants, etc. - diversification.

We've yield farmed large portions of last year but have closed these positions as currently it's simply not worth the risk/reward. Both UST and FTX were a close call, but funds were pulled from there in time. To experience this a third time simply isn't worth 5-6% APY right now.

It is great that you'll are intending to buy from the secondary market as well. I did notice that the investments slowed down and you'll are focusing on bigger ticket sizes too. Yes, it is healthy to have a big cash position. But there are no new products under development right, atleast for this year as per your yearly outlook letter you'll published. Also, there's a opportunity cost as well to the cash held idle so was concerned. And yes, yield farming is not worth it right now. The risk is too much for the reward. But in this day and age, it might not require paying to learn these.

Just my 2 cents, obviously paid courses have their advantages but if you're a looking to be a freelancer, you'll likely need to learn many things on the job and learning where to get the information you need (without incurring costs) is probably one of the most important aspects.

Just example, wordpress and shopify wouldn't be the only platforms that provide wysiwyg web builders and you might need to learn at least some basic html, css(probably the most important) to better design websites. If you're going to focus on wordpress, would also be beneficial to know a little bit of php to be able to edit the backend files.

And if you're going to do Social media management/marketing, would also make sense to cover the other platforms like google ads, tiktok, instagram, etc. On top of which, Search Engine Optimization (SEO) will also be very helpful.

Virtual assistant is interesting, I believe apple is hiring virtual assistants but I'm not sure what the requirements are. Might be best to look at the requirements and work backwards from there although this isn't really freelancing anymore.
